<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900801-0019</DOCNO><DOCID>900801-0019.</DOCID><HL>   House Passes Bill to Lift   Federal Borrowing Limit</HL><DATE>08/01/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16</SO><CO>   LABOR</CO><IN>ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)</IN><GV>HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES (HHS)CONGRESS (CNG)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The House passed and sent to the Senate abill that would raise the federal borrowing limit to $3.444trillion from $3.122 trillion, sufficient to allow governmentborrowing through September 1991.   Congressional leaders expect the bill to bog down in theSenate and a shorter-term extension to take its place. Ashort-term alternative already has been moving in the Houseeven as the lawmakers voted yesterday. The House Ways andMeans Committee has approved a measure that would authorizethe Treasury to keep borrowing through Oct. 15. This versionmay reach the House floor later this week. The Treasury saysit will default unless Congress lifts the debt ceiling byAug. 15.</LP><TEXT>   The congressional recess is scheduled to begin Friday,although Senate leaders say they may delay their departure inorder to continue working on a deficit-reduction package.   Yesterday's debt bill, which was approved 221-205,included a provision backed by Rep. Byron Dorgan (D., N.D.)that would remove the Social Security Trust Fund from theGramm-Rudman calculation of the federal budget deficit.</TEXT></DOC>